    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-03-18T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-03-18T15:00:00-05:00" n="68"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d68">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">762.71/43a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Rumania</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gunther</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-03-18T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 18, 1939—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>29. The <hi rend="italic">New York Times</hi> this morning carries an article
                    from London that “a virtual ultimatum had been issued by Germany to Rumania to
                    the effect that (1) Rumania should give up certain industries and (2) should
                    agree that her entire exports of grain, oil, lumber, cattle and foodstuffs
                    should go exclusively to Germany, in return for which Germany would be ready to
                    guarantee Rumanian territorial integrity.”</p>
                <pb facs="0085" n="73" xml:id="pg_73"/>
                <p>Kennedy quotes the Rumanian Minister in London as confirming the general
                    substance but as saying that the demands were made a week or 10 days ago when
                        Wohlthat<note n="19" xml:id="d68fn19">Helmuth Wohlthat, Economic Adviser to
                        Marshal Goering.</note> was in Bucharest.</p>
                <p>The Rumanian Minister here<note n="20" xml:id="d68fn20">Radu Irimescu.</note>
                    informs the Department that knowledge of these demands has reunited all elements
                    in Rumania and that Maniu<note n="21" xml:id="d68fn21">Julius Maniu, founder of
                        Rumanian National Peasant Party; Premier, 1928–31.</note> and others are now
                    subordinating politics to national unity.</p>
                <p>Please telegraph such information as you can gain and analytic comments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
